== Production ==
=== Development ===
The 1961 American [[Romantic comedy film|romantic comedy film]] ''[[Come September]]'', featuring [[Rock Hudson]] and [[Gina Lollobrigida]], and directed by [[Robert Mulligan]], was a worldwide box office success, especially in [[Chennai]].<ref name = "BFTP Guy"/> The film narrated the tale of Robert (Hudson), an American millionaire, who arrives at his villa for his vacation. His girlfriend, Lisa (Lollobrigida), has given up waiting for him and has decided to marry another man. Robert's villa manager, Maurice ([[Walter Slezak]]), converts the villa into a hotel while Robert is away. The villa is now occupied by a group of young American girls trying to fend off a gang of boys, led by Tony ([[Bobby Darin]]).<ref name = "BFTP Guy"/> [[A. C. Tirulokchandar]], who was then a screenwriter for AVM Productions, adapted the screenplay of ''Come September'' into ''Anbe Vaa''.<ref name = "BFTP Guy">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/anbe-vaa-1966/article4084816.ece|title=Anbe Vaa 1966|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|author=[[Randor Guy]]|date=10 November 2012|accessdate=26 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141126044933/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/anbe-vaa-1966/article4084816.ece|archivedate=26 November 2014}}</ref> Tirulokchandar was introduced to AVM Productions by [[S. A. Ashokan]], who he had worked with previously as an assistant director on ''Vijayapuri Veeran'' (1960). It was Ashokan who helped Tirulokchandar cast Ramachandran in the film.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://tamil.thehindu.com/cinema/cinema-others/%E0%AE%AA%E0%AF%86%E0%AE%A3%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A3%E0%AF%88%E0%AE%95%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%95%E0%AE%9F%E0%AE%A4%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%A9%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%85%E0%AE%9A%E0%AF%8B%E0%AE%95%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%AA%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%B0%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%9F%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%9F%E0%AE%BF-%E0%AE%AE%E0%AE%95%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%B4%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A8%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%8E%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%9C%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%86%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D/article5734323.ece | title=<U+0BAA><U+0BC6><U+0BA3><U+0BCD><U+0BA3><U+0BC8><U+0B95><U+0BCD> <U+0B95><U+0B9F><U+0BA4><U+0BCD><U+0BA4><U+0BBF><U+0BA9><U+0BBE><U+0BB0><U+0BCD> <U+0B85><U+0B9A><U+0BCB><U+0B95><U+0BA9><U+0BCD>- <U+0BAA><U+0BBE><U+0BB0><U+0BBE><U+0B9F><U+0BCD><U+0B9F><U+0BBF> <U+0BAE><U+0B95><U+0BBF><U+0BB4><U+0BCD><U+0BA8><U+0BCD><U+0BA4><U+0BBE><U+0BB0><U+0BCD> <U+0B8E><U+0BAE><U+0BCD>.<U+0B9C><U+0BBF>.<U+0B86><U+0BB0><U+0BCD>! (Ashokan kidnapped a woman - MGR praises him!) | work=The Hindu | date=28 February 2014 | accessdate=8 December 2014 | author=Nelba | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141208082726/http://tamil.thehindu.com/cinema/cinema-others/%E0%AE%AA%E0%AF%86%E0%AE%A3%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A3%E0%AF%88%E0%AE%95%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%95%E0%AE%9F%E0%AE%A4%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%A9%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%85%E0%AE%9A%E0%AF%8B%E0%AE%95%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%AA%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%B0%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%9F%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%9F%E0%AE%BF-%E0%AE%AE%E0%AE%95%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%B4%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A8%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%8E%E0%AE%AE%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%9C%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%86%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D/article5734323.ece | archivedate=8 December 2014}}</ref>

[[Javar Seetharaman]] also contributed to the film's screenplay,{{efn|Sylvian's references and trivia about the film are credited to the book by [[M. Saravanan]], titled ''AVM 60 cinema''.<ref name="Sylvian">{{cite web | url=http://www.sylvianism.com/2009/07/21/50-tamil-movies-to-watch-before-you-die-10/ | title=50 Tamil Movies to watch before you die | publisher=Sylvianism.com | date=21 July 2009 | accessdate=26 November 2014 | author=Sylvian | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141126044635/http://www.sylvianism.com/2009/07/21/50-tamil-movies-to-watch-before-you-die-10/ | archivedate=26 November 2014}}</ref>}} as did Aaroor Das, who wrote the film's dialogue.{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=234}} Director [[S. P. Muthuraman]] worked as an assistant director on the film.{{sfn|Ramachandran|2012|page=86}} The original budget was {{INR}} 600,000 (US$ 2.874 million in 1966).{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=235}}{{efn|The exchange rate in 1966 was 4.79 Indian rupees ({{INR}}) per 1 US dollar (US$).<ref name="value">{{cite web | url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2013-08-24/news/41444029_1_indian-rupee-american-currency-continued-dollar-demand | title=Rupee's journey since Independence: Down by 65 times against dollar | work=[[The Economic Times]] | date=24 August 2013 | accessdate=6 December 2014 | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130829085318/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2013-08-24/news/41444029_1_indian-rupee-american-currency-continued-dollar-demand | archivedate=29 August 2013}}</ref>|name = exchange1966}} S. Maruthi Rao, R. G. Gope and A. K. Shekar were in charge of the cinematography, editing, and art direction, respectively.{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=234}} [[Raghuram]] made his cinematic debut with this film, working as an assistant choreographer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/Choreographer-Raghuram-Passes-Away/2013/12/01/article1921288.ece|title=Choreographer Raghuram Passes Away|newspaper=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=1 December 2013|accessdate=26 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141126061335/http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/Choreographer-Raghuram-Passes-Away/2013/12/01/article1921288.ece|archivedate=26 November 2014}}</ref>

=== Casting ===
{{quote box
| quote ="I found him [M. G. Ramachandran] smiling throughout the storytelling session. At the end he said, <U+2018>I'll do it. We will be mere puppets in your hands and the credit will go only to you.' <U+2018>AV' was a smashing hit, and I was moved when he repeated the words at the film's 100th day function."
| source =&nbsp;<U+2013> Tirulokchandar, on how Ramachadran was cast.<ref name = "Tirulok">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/moorings-and-musings/article1567568.ece|title=Moorings and musings|newspaper=The Hindu|author=Malathi Rangarajan|date=24 March 2011|accessdate=27 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141127113934/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/moorings-and-musings/article1567568.ece|archivedate=27 November 2014}}</ref>
| align = right
| width = 30%
}}
''Anbe Vaa'' marked the first time where AVM wrote a script to suit an actor's image and acting style; prior to this they had chosen actors to fit an already completed script.{{sfn|Ramachandran|2012|page=147}} While Tirulokchandar was writing the script, [[A. V. Meiyappan]] made the suggestion to approach Ramachandran for the lead role. Tirulokchandar found this intriguing, as the script's genre was dissimilar to what Ramachandran was noted for: action-adventure or social and family dramas which portrayed him as a champion for the downtrodden.<ref name = "Tirulok"/> 

When approached, Ramachandran readily accepted the role and was excited about doing it,{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=235}} giving the film priority in his schedule.{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=235}} Ramachandran gave a [[Daily call sheet|call sheet]] of seventy two days for participating in the film.{{Sfn|Saravanan|2005|page=170}} He was paid a salary of {{INR}} 300,000-325,000 for his participation in the film;{{efn|[[G. Dhananjayan]] and Saravanan state in their books that M. G. Ramachandran was paid {{INR}} 325,000,{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=235}}<ref name = "Sylvian"/> whereas ''[[The Economic Times]]'' states that he was paid {{INR}} 300,000.<ref name = "AVTOI"/>}} however, it turned out to be his only collaboration with both Tirulokchandar and AVM Productions.{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=234}}<ref name = "Tirulok"/>

Ramachandran initially recommended [[K. A. Thangavelu]] for the role of Punyakodi, but [[M. Saravanan (film producer)|M. Saravanan]], one of the film's producers, said that his father, A. V. Meiyappan, wanted [[T. R. Ramachandran]] in the role. M.G. Ramachandran accepted the decision and told Saravanan not to tell T. R. Ramachandran about his initial choice.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/interview-with-avm-saravanan/article6594598.ece | title=A word kept | date=13 November 2014 | accessdate=26 November 2014 | author=Malathi Rangarajan | newspaper=The Hindu | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141113165714/http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/interview-with-avm-saravanan/article6594598.ece | archivedate=13 November 2014}}</ref> M. G. Ramachandran also recommended [[Jayalalithaa]] for the role of Geetha, but when the producers disagreed with that selection, Ramachandran then suggested [[B. Saroja Devi]], who was given the role.{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=235}}

=== Filming ===
''Anbe Vaa'' was the first film of AVM Productions to be made in [[Eastman Color]].<ref name = "Sylvian"/> [[Principal photography]] for the film began with a ''[[Puja (Hinduism)|puja]]''{{efn|''Puja'' is a prayer ritual performed by [[Hindu]]s to host, honour and worship one or more deities, or to spiritually celebrate an event.{{Sfn|Lochtefeld|2002|pages=529-530}}}} ceremony held on 12 August 1965. Filming was completed within five months, the quickest completion for any film starring M. G. Ramachandran.{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page = 235}} Ramachandran received special permission to go by car to shoot the film in exotic locations in Shimla; a privilege allowed only to the governor of the state. Under the auspices of that permission, the entire unit went to Shimla.{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=235}} The song "Pudhiya Vaanam" was shot in the small hill station of [[Kufri, India|Kufri]], located 13 kilometres from Shimla, as well as at [[Mall Road, Shimla]].<ref name = "Making"/>

Savi, an editor who worked for the Tamil magazine, ''[[Ananda Vikatan]]'', accompanied the production unit and published an article on the making of the film.{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=235}} Although the story is set in Shimla, 95% of the film was shot in [[Ooty]], with some scenes being filmed in [[Jammu and Kashmir]],{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=235}} making it the second Tamil film after ''[[Then Nilavu]]'' (1961) to be shot there.{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=234}} "Naan Paarthathilae" was one of the few songs in the film that was shot outdoors, due to Ramachandran not wanting to attract attention from his large fan following.<ref name = "Sylvian"/> During shooting in Ooty, Ramachandran personally bought sweaters for the entire cast and crew.<ref name = "Making"/>

The production unit, composed of 20 crew members, along with Tirulokchandar, M. G. Ramachandran, Saroja Devi and Savi, initially flew to Delhi. From Delhi, they travelled to [[Kalka]] by train, then continued on to Shimla, using three first-generation [[Chevrolet Impala]]s.<ref name = "Making">{{cite web|url=http://www.adrasaka.com/2012/05/blog-post_2999.html|title=<U+0B85><U+0BA9><U+0BCD><U+0BAA><U+0BC7> <U+0BB5><U+0BBE> - <U+0B8E><U+0BAE><U+0BCD> <U+0B9C><U+0BBF> <U+0B86><U+0BB0><U+0BCD> - <U+0BB7><U+0BC2><U+0B9F><U+0BCD><U+0B9F><U+0BBF><U+0B99><U+0BCD><U+0B95><U+0BCD> - <U+0BB5><U+0BBF><U+0B95><U+0B9F><U+0BA9><U+0BCD> <U+0BAA><U+0BCA><U+0B95><U+0BCD><U+0B95><U+0BBF><U+0BB7> <U+0BAA><U+0B95><U+0BCD><U+0B95><U+0B99><U+0BCD><U+0B95><U+0BB3><U+0BCD>. (Making of Anbe Vaa - Ananda Vikatan)|publisher=Adrasaka.com|magazine=[[Ananda Vikatan]]|author=Savi|date=29 May 2012|archivedate=26 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141126080748/http://www.adrasaka.com/2012/05/blog-post_2999.html|archivedate=26 November 2014}}</ref> The skating scenes in the film, involving Ramachandran and Saroja Devi, were completed in two days. Both Ramachandran and Saroja Devi were initially hesitant to perform the scene, but went through with it after they received encouragement from the local population.<ref name = "Making"/> During post-production, the sound effect of the horses' footfall in "Rajavin Paarvai" was created by [[Meesai Murugesan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/Meesai-Murugesan-Redefined-Music-Effects/2014/11/09/article2514657.ece|title='Meesai' Murugesan Redefined Music Effects|newspaper=The New Indian Express|author=J. Santhosh|date=9 November 2014|accessdate=28 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141128033615/http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/Meesai-Murugesan-Redefined-Music-Effects/2014/11/09/article2514657.ece|archivedate=28 November 2014}}</ref>

