== Release ==
With a final length of {{Convert|4855|metres|feet}}, ''Anbe Vaa'' was released on 14 January 1966, and was promoted as "an innovative entertainment film" by its producers.{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=234}} AVM Productions sold the film's distribution rights for {{INR}} 3.3 million (US$ 15.807 million in 1966),{{efn|name = exchange1966}} which was the highest amount in the Tamil film industry up until that point.{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=235}} Although the film had a theatrical run of 23 weeks and was a box office success,{{Sfn|Saravanan|2005|page=178}} AVM Productions earned a profit of only {{INR}} 300,000 (US$ 1.437 million in 1966),{{efn|name = exchange1966}} due to the film's large budget. The film was dubbed into [[Telugu cinema|Telugu]] as ''Prema Manasulu''.{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=235}}

On 18 April 2010, the film was screened at the [[South Indian Film Chamber of Commerce|South Indian Film Chamber Theatre]] for the Dignity Film Festival held in Chennai; other films also screened included ''[[Madhumati]]'' (1958), ''[[Kadhalikka Neramillai]]'' (1964), ''[[Server Sundaram]]'' (1964) and ''[[Thillana Mohanambal]]'' (1968).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chennaimirror.com/pressnews/topstories_190410_4.html|title=Dignity Foundation announces the opening of first of its kind Film Festival for the 50+ citizens|work=Chennai Mirror|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141010135845/http://www.chennaimirror.com/pressnews/topstories_190410_4.html|date=17 April 2010|archivedate=10 October 2014|accessdate=27 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/the-good-ole-days/article785628.ece|title=The good ole days|newspaper=The Hindu|date=17 April 2010|accessdate=27 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141127070134/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/the-good-ole-days/article785628.ece|archivedate=27 November 2014}}</ref>

=== Critical reception ===
On 6 August 1966, the review in ''Ananda Vikatan'' said, "The film was an English film in Tamil... The film does not have any story. One can spend three hours in an entertaining manner with this film..."{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=235}} Randor Guy, in his review, wrote, "The screenplay was brilliantly written by ACT. MGR<U+2019>s performance as the rich man posing as a tenant was impressive. Nagesh was inimitable. Saroja Devi looked glamorous in her glossy make-up and costume." He went on to conclude that the film would be "Remembered for the impressive performances by MGR, Nagesh and Saroja Devi, melodious music, interesting storyline and screenplay, picturesque cinematography which captured the beautiful landscape of the Himalayan region, and the fabulous sets in true AVM style."<ref name = "BFTP Guy"/> G. Dhananjayan commented, "The film stood out for its comedy, memorable songs and dances, rich making and locations.", and said that the main reason for the film's success was that it was "an out-and-out entertainer".{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=235}}

Pavithra Srinivasan of [[Rediff.com]] called Saroja Devi, "a style icon", and rated this as "her best" performance, comparing it with her role in ''[[Enga Veettu Pillai]]'' (1965).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://specials.rediff.com/movies/2008/jul/01slide6.htm|title=A style icon|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|author=Pavithra Srinivasan|date=1 July 2008|archivedate=27 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141127050902/http://specials.rediff.com/movies/2008/jul/01slide6.htm|accessdate=27 November 2014}}</ref> [[Sify]] called Nagesh's on-screen chemistry with M. G. Ramachandran in the film "fantastic", further elaborating that, "In this film the MGR-Nagesh scenes according to a veteran distributor brought repeat audiences to the theatres. He played the hero's sidekick and was simply terrific."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/10-best-films-of-late-nagesh-news-tamil-kkfsx3ccfbhsi.html|title=10 Best Films of late Nagesh|publisher=[[Sify]]|date=1 February 2009|archivedate=23 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141123070732/http://www.sify.com/movies/10-best-films-of-late-nagesh-news-tamil-kkfsx3ccfbhsi.html|accessdate=27 November 2014}}</ref> Behindwoods.com referred to the relationship between M. G. Ramachandran and S. A. Ashokan in the film as "a perfect example" of friendship"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-slide-shows/movie-1/friendship/tamil-cinema-friendship-anbe-vaa.html|title=Anbe Vaa <U+2013> MGR and Ashokan|publisher=Behindwoods.com|accessdate=27 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141127112553/http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-slide-shows/movie-1/friendship/tamil-cinema-friendship-anbe-vaa.html|archivedate=27 November 2014}}</ref> IndiaGlitz said the film was "A classic romantic entertainer Tamil film patrons wouldn<U+2019>t want to forget."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/epic-romances-who-replaces-who--tamil-news-77995|title=Epic romances - Who replaces who?|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=14 February 2012|archivedate=27 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141127071700/http://www.indiaglitz.com/epic-romances-who-replaces-who--tamil-news-77995|accessdate=27 November 2014}}</ref>

== Legacy ==
M. G. Ramachandran, who specialised in films based mainly on action and family subjects, handled a comedic part for the first time in his career in this film, proving his ability to handle that genre.{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=235}} ''Anbe Vaa'' was one of several films featuring Ramachandran which he used to propagate his ideologies during his election campaigns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/2004/09/30/stories/2004093006920400.htm|title=Passage from the reel to real life not easy|author=[[Sudhish Kamath]]|newspaper=The Hindu|date=30 September 2004|accessdate=27 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141127082449/http://www.thehindu.com/2004/09/30/stories/2004093006920400.htm|archivedate=27 November 2014}}</ref> The film inspired several later films in Tamil, which focused mainly on conflicts between lovers, as well as entertainment aspects, notable of which include ''[[Kushi (2000 film)|Kushi]]'' (2000), ''[[Lovely (2001 film)|Lovely]]'' (2001), and ''[[Thiruda Thirudi]]'' (2003).{{sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=235}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/2001/06/22/stories/09220226.htm|title=All for a lovely time|newspaper=The Hindu|author=S. R. Ashok Kumar|date=22 June 2001|accessdate=27 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141127075117/http://www.thehindu.com/2001/06/22/stories/09220226.htm|archivedate=27 November 2014}}</ref> The film was one of the first [[Cinema of South India|South Indian films]] to be shot in Shimla, inspiring many other films to utilise Shimla as a shooting location, notably the [[Telugu cinema|Telugu film]], ''[[Desamuduru]]'' (2007).{{sfn|Chaudhry|2012|page=57}}

[[Mani Ratnam]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/article2272999.ece|title=Filmmakers<U+2019> favourites|newspaper=The Hindu|date=13 July 2007|accessdate=27 November 2014|author=S. R. Ashok Kumar|accessdate=27 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141011060705/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/article2272999.ece|archivedate=11 October 2014}}</ref> [[M. S. Guhan]]'s daughter Aruna Guhan,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indulge.newindianexpress.com/rewind-remix-replay/chennai/19262|title=Rewind, Remix & Replay|newspaper=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=17 October 2014|accessdate=27 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141127080606/http://indulge.newindianexpress.com/rewind-remix-replay/chennai/19262|archivedate=27 November 2014}}</ref> [[Prabhu Deva]], and [[Sundar C.]] all ranked ''Anbe Vaa'' among their favourite films.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/love-everywhere/article1553140.ecee|title=Love Everywhere|newspaper=The Hindu|date=19 March 2011|accessdate=27 November 2014|author=S. R. Ashok Kumar|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141127072521/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/love-everywhere/article1553140.ece|archivedate=27 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/slice-of-the-city/article871493.ece|title=Slice of the city|newspaper=The Hindu|date=7 November 2010|accessdate=27 November 2014|author=S. R. Ashok Kumar|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141127072514/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/slice-of-the-city/article871493.ece|archivedate=27 November 2014}}</ref> The costumes that Ramachandran used in the film,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/history-created-and-preserved/article896098.ece|title=History created <U+2026> and preserved!|author1=Malathi Rangarajan|author2=MRN|newspaper=The Hindu|date=19 February 2010|accessdate=27 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141127084618/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/history-created-and-preserved/article896098.ece|archivedate=27 November 2014}}</ref> as well as the carriage used for "Rajavin Paarvai", are preserved at AVM Studios.<ref name ="Rekhs"/> ''The Hindu'' included "Pudhiya Vaanam" in its list of the "Immortal songs of TMS",{{efn|TMS refers to T. M. Soundararajan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/monarch-of-melody/article2273070.ece|title=Monarch of melody|newspaper=The Hindu|author=Uma S. Maheshwari|date=20 July 2007|accessdate=27 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141127090921/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/monarch-of-melody/article2273070.ece|archivedate=27 November 2014}}</ref>}} and also among lyricist Vaali's best songs in their collection, "Best of Vaali: From 1964 - 2013".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-one-and-only-vaalee/article4931661.ece|title=The one and only Vaalee|newspaper=The Hindu|author=Malathi Rangarajan|date=19 July 2013|accessdate=27 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141127090724/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-one-and-only-vaalee/article4931661.ece|archivedate=27 November 2014}}</ref>

=== In popular culture ===
References to ''Anbe Vaa'' are made in various films. The 1988 film ''[[Puthiya Vaanam]]'', starring [[Sivaji Ganesan]], was named after the song of the same name.{{sfn|Rajadhyaksha|Willemen|2014|p=98}} In ''[[Raja Kaiya Vacha]]'' (1990), Raja ([[Prabhu Ganesan|Prabhu]]) is seen watching "Rajavin Paarvai" on television.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sVC2ur5G9KE|title=Raja Kaiya Vecha|publisher=Tamil Matinee|date=28 June 2014|accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref> Films like ''[[Rajavin Parvaiyile]]'' (1995),<ref>{{cite web | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Vijays-mom-a-fan-of-Ajith/articleshow/19661771.cms | title=Vijay<U+2019>s mom, a fan of Ajith | work=The Times of India | date=21 April 2013 | accessdate=5 December 2014 | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141205144948/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Vijays-mom-a-fan-of-Ajith/articleshow/19661771.cms | archivedate=5 December 2014}}</ref> and ''[[Love Birds (1996 film)|Love Birds]]'' (1996), were also named after the songs from ''Anbe Vaa''.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=lblOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Px8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=3954,2615390&dq=love+birds+nagma&hl=en | title=A twist to the typical love story | work=[[The New Straits Times]] | date=6 February 1996 | accessdate=5 December 2014 | author=K. Vijiyan}}</ref> In ''[[Unakkaga Ellam Unakkaga]]'' (1999), Kundalakesi ([[Goundamani]]) imagines himself as M. G. Ramachandran in "Pudhiya Vaanam" by dancing with children, the result of which is him being mistaken for a kidnapper by the police.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D20hthocpsM|title=Unakkaga Ellam Unakkaga|publisher=Tamil Matinee|date=30 July 2014|accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref>

In ''[[Dhool]]'' (2003), [[Vikram (actor)|Vikram]]'s character, Aarumugam, echoes a single line, "Pudhiya Vaanam", to signal his arrival to his friends.<ref>''Dhool (DVD)''. clip from 19:00 to 19:10.</ref> In 2005, another film called ''[[Anbe Vaa (2005 film)|Anbe Vaa]]'', starring actors Thendral, Sridevika and [[Vivek (actor)|Vivek]] in the lead roles, was released; while its critical response was average,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/anbe-vaa-review-tamil-14013685.html|title=Anbe Vaa|publisher=Sify|accessdate=27 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141127101028/http://www.sify.com/movies/anbe-vaa-review-tamil-14013685.html|archivedate=27 November 2014}}</ref> it was a box office success.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/features/News/News36/3-11-05/tamil-movies-news-vivek.html|title=Vivek back in his elements in Anbe Vaa|publisher=Behindwoods.com|date=3 November 2005|accessdate=27 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141127103148/http://www.behindwoods.com/features/News/News36/3-11-05/tamil-movies-news-vivek.html|archivedate=27 November 2014}}</ref> A song with the same title as the film is used in ''[[Thotta]]'' (2008).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/review/sst/20080205.htm|title=Thotta's music has no lingering quality|publisher=Rediff.com|author=Saraswathy Srinivas|date=5 February 2008|accessdate=8 December 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141208080347/http://www.rediff.com/movies/review/sst/20080205.htm|archivedate=8 December 2014}}</ref> A clip from the song "Love Birds" is featured in the [[Venkat Prabhu]] film ''[[Saroja (film)|Saroja]]'' (2008).<ref>''Saroja (DVD)''. clip from 1:33:50 to 1:34:00.</ref> Scenes from the film were interposed in ''[[Villu (film)|Villu]]'' (2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/the-focus-is-clear-villu/article3021033.ece|title=The focus is clear - Villu|author=Malathi Rangarajan|newspaper=The Hindu|date=16 January 2009|accessdate=27 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141127085837/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/the-focus-is-clear-villu/article3021033.ece|archivedate=27 November 2014}}</ref> A portion of "Rajavin Paarvai" is used in the song "Vaa Machi" from ''[[Onbadhule Guru]]'' (2013).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/songs-to-perk-up-your-mood/article4446258.ece|title=Songs to perk up your mood|newspaper=The Hindu|author=S. R. Ashok Kumar|date=23 February 2013|accessdate=26 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141126172337/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/songs-to-perk-up-your-mood/article4446258.ece|archivedate=26 November 2014}}</ref>

In 2002, a quiz programme called ''Pudhiya Vaanam Pudhiya Bhoomi'' aired on [[DD National]] and DD Podhigai to help develop tourism in [[Tamil Nadu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/lf/2002/01/18/stories/2002011801690200.htm|title=Talk of the town|newspaper=The Hindu|author1=T. S. Shankar|author2=Ramya Kannan|author3=[[Sudhish Kamath]]|date=18 January 2002|accessdate=27 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141127091607/http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/lf/2002/01/18/stories/2002011801690200.htm|archivedate=27 November 2014}}</ref> In 2009, a television series titled ''Anbe Vaa'' aired on [[STAR Vijay]] every Monday-Thursday at 8:00 pm [[Indian Standard Time|IST]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/jun-09-04/anbe-vaa-22-06-09.html|title=Anbe Vaa, again|publisher=Behindwoods.com|date=22 June 2009|accessdate=27 November 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141127091927/http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/jun-09-04/anbe-vaa-22-06-09.html|archivedate=27 November 2014}}</ref>

